<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Japan cuts discount rate by 0.75 points to 3.75%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of Japan, the country's central bank, early today cut the official
discount rate by 0.75 points to 3.75 per cent in response to the rapid
weakening of the Japanese economy.
The cut came a day after the Tokyo stock market plunged to its lowest level
in five years as investors showed disappointment with a government economic
package aimed at stimulating the economy.
Share prices fell further in initial trading this morning, with the Nikkei
average down nearly 300 points shortly after opening.
The rate cut is the biggest since the central bank began to ease monetary
policy last summer, when the ODR stood at 6 per cent. It indicates growing
concern in the bank over the rapid decline in economic indicators over the
past two months.
The bank last cut the interest rate in late December, but the reduction has
had no appreciable impact on the economy, with industrial output declining
and monetary growth at an historic low.
News that the cut was coming was leaked to the Japanese press yesterday but
stock market investors failed to respond positively. After a slight rise
initially, the Nikkei average on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped yesterday
by 323.36 on the day to close at 19,345.95
'Sentiment is so poor that I don't think the market would be happy with
anything now,' said Mr Craig Chudler, strategist at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew.
The market is standing more than 50 per cent below the highs reached more
than two years ago.
The 0.75 point rate cut, compared with earlier cuts of half a point, is
likely to be the last reduction for some time. Economists have argued that
potential borrowers needed to believe that rates have hit bottom before they
will take on fresh debt and increase spending. A cut of this size signals
that the Bank of Japan's overriding concern of recent years to control
inflation has been replaced by worries about the health of the economy.
The government yesterday said its emergency economic measures would boost
demand by at least Y4,000bn (Pounds 17bn) in the first half of the fiscal
year (which begins today) compared with the same period a year ago.
But private economists said increased spending over current budgets in the
first half of the year would be much smaller and the actual impact of the
package difficult to detect.
</TEXT>
