<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Election 1992: Polls reflect concern over health policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and GARETH SMYTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DELAYED reaction to Labour's health broadcast and adverse voter reaction
to Conservative 'negative campaigning' were the reasons Mr Neil Kinnock's
team gave for the sharp upturn in his campaign's poll fortunes yesterday.
At least part of that thesis appeared to be borne out in the detailed
figures behind the Mori poll for The Times. It showed 56 per cent naming the
National Health Service as their chief concern - a 10-point rise from the
beginning of the election campaign.
A total of 53 per cent of voters believed that the NHS was unsafe in Mr John
Major's hands, against 38 per cent who held that it was safe.
Worse still for the Conservatives, 57 per cent do not believe the
government's assurances that it would not privatise the NHS, against 32 per
cent accepting its word.
The findings were also damaging for Conservative strategists. Some 65 per
cent of Liberal Democrats and 56 per cent of Labour supporters believed
their parties had the best campaigns. Only 24 per cent of Tories would make
the same claim. Tax was named by only 15 per cent of all polled as likely to
affect their vote.
The Harris poll for ITN showed a fall in Tory support among women and
semi-skilled workers, designated C2s. Support had fallen five points among
both groups to 36 points and 28 points respectively.
In the ICM poll for The Guardian 81 per cent of Labour supporters said they
were certain to vote, against 83 per cent for the Liberal Democrats but 76
per cent for the Tories.
A poll by Bath University put Mr Chris Patten, the Conservative party
chairman, on 39.5 per cent, one point behind the Liberal Democrat challenger
Mr Don Foster. The poll sample was 871 and the university quoted a 3.5 per
cent margin of error.
A local poll in Birmingham Northfield suggested that Labour is set to
capture the marginal seat from the Tories.
</TEXT>
