<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Lloyd's 1989 losses may reach Pounds 1.65bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOSSES at the Lloyd's of London insurance market for 1989 could reach almost
Pounds 1.65bn according to figures circulated yesterday by the Association
of Lloyd's Members. The association represents more than 9,000 Names, the
individuals whose assets back underwriting at Lloyd's.
Financial Intelligence &amp; Research, a consultant to the association, has
offered best and worst-case scenarios for 1989 results based on provisional
estimates supplied by Lloyd's agents. The best-case scenario would be a loss
of Pounds 1.06bn.
But the association warned in a newsletter that the figures may not include
estimates for asbestosis and pollution reserves. Other factors including US
tax charges may make a significant difference to the 1989 result, which
Lloyd's will report in June.
Meanwhile, Names on Gooda Walker syndicates, which face losses of more than
Pounds 200m for 1989, have warned of new legal action if negotiations
designed to prevent payment of cash calls are unsuccessful.
Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg, chairman of the Gooda Walker Action Group, said
his committee had been involved in 'intense discussion' over the past 10
days with GW Run Off, which has managed the Gooda Walker syndicates since
the agency went into liquidation last year. He said GW Run Off had also been
in contact with Lloyd's over the same issue.
The Names will seek injunctions to prevent Lloyd's drawing down deposits
held with their agents, irrespective of the result of a separate legal
action by more than 820 Names which was postponed yesterday until Monday in
the Commercial Court. Insurance companies are to be offered rent reductions
to continue support for the London Underwriting Centre, an insurance company
exchange. Its opening was delayed by a fire last August.
Market Building, a joint venture backed by 24 leading European and US
insurers, hopes that the exchange can eventually rival Lloyd's in size and
sophistication.
But August's fire was a big setback to Market Building, which owns a 25-year
lease on the property at Minster Court in the City of London. Damage of
Pounds 125m was insured, but the fire has delayed opening of the centre
until October next year and has freed more than 70 would-be tenants from
their earlier commitments.
</TEXT>
