<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / British Gas set for clash over pricing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS is heading for a row with its regulator over its plan to raise
the price it charges rivals to transport gas through its pipeline.
The rises are shown in a document published by the company today which
suggests changes that would simplify its pricing structure for gas
transportation. British Gas is inviting comment before issuing a price list
in August.
But Sir James McKinnon, director-general of Ofgas, the industry regulator,
said yesterday: 'The pipeline business is a low or no-risk business and
there is no reason for its rate of return to be higher than the current
level, and maybe that's even too high.'
British Gas is currently allowed by the regulator to make a 4.5 per cent
return on its gas transport business.
Prices for transporting gas are likely to rise even if British Gas is
prevented from raising its rate of return on the business. That is because
British Gas has previously not tried to make a 4.5 per cent return across
all of its price bands.
The new British Gas structure would simplify pricing by evening out the
differences in prices charged across the country and unifying them in a
price schedule.
Under the present system, shippers must ask for an individual quotation for
delivering gas to one particular site.
The proposals for a new pricing structure are in response to demands by the
Office of Fair Trading that British Gas hive off its transportation unit
into a separate subsidiary.
</TEXT>
