FT  01 APR 92 / O&amp;Y to seek Tube discussion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK, the property developer, expects to hold talks with the
government after the general election about financing the Pounds 1.3bn
Jubilee line Underground extension to London's Docklands.
The company yesterday failed to make its first contribution of Pounds 40m to
the project as originally scheduled. It is engaged in talks with its banks
about the restructuring of worldwide debt estimated at more than Dollars
20bn (Pounds 11.56bn).
Under an initial agreement reached with the government and London Regional
transport in November 1989, a further contribution from O&amp;Y was due by this
time next year, with the balance of Pounds 300m expected on completion of
the Tube extention in 1996.
Bankers say they are reluctant to put up the Pounds 400m originally promised
by O&amp;Y as its contribution to the Jubilee building costs.
But they fear that the value of Canary Wharf, Europe's biggest new
development of offices, to which they have lent Pounds 700m, will be
impaired if the extension is not built.
One possibility being mooted is that O&amp;Y and its banks would contribute some
funds to the line, although probably not the full Pounds 400m.
This would put the onus on the future UK government to decide by how much to
increase its own financing of the project. The Department of Tranpsort and
the Labour party are holding back from making any firm commitments to the
financial future of the extention while O&amp;Y fails to meet its own financial
commitments.
O&amp;Y's financial difficulties are being watched closely by several local and
international construction companies which have put in bids for contracts
worth up to Pounds 1.5bn linked to the building of the extention.
