FT  01 APR 92 / Canadian will lead group bidding for Channel 5
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MOSES ZNAIMER, the Canadian broadcaster who founded City TV in Toronto,
is to lead a bid for a Channel 5 licence in the UK.
He is to be chief executive of Five TV, which plans to bid for the licence
which is expected to be advertised soon.
Channel 5 should be able to reach three quarters of the UK audience by
conventional transmitters. The winner of the bidding process have to pay for
the transmitters and for the retuning of several million video recorders now
using the frequencies that Channel 5 will use.
If Five TV wins, Mr Znaimer, a former actor and merchant banker, will live
in the UK. Five TV is negotiating with potential backers including Time
Warner, the world's largest media company, Thames Television and Columbia of
the US.
The battle for Channel 5 looks like turning into a battle principally
between two powerful rivals with different concepts of broadcasting,
although there will be other bidders.
Five TV will seek to adapt the Toronto model of news, films and music to the
UK market. It will create a series of city stations beginning with London
and moving on quickly to Birmingham and Manchester. Each city will have two
to three hours a night of local news plus a national schedule which will
concentrate on music and films.
The other main bidder is Mr Silvio Berlusconi's Fininvest, which is likely
to concentrate on a national channel featuring glossy entertainment.
'What has to be decided is whether the UK has another generalised,
homogenised, bits-of-something channel or something new and innovative,' Mr
Znaimer said yesterday. 'I'm not selling tonnage (of audience); I'm selling
precision.'
He believes the UK regulator - the Independent Television Commission - has a
clear choice. He says its members can see Mr Berlusconi's channels in Milan
or a different model of television broadcasting on his own network in
Toronto.
He believes the UK is the best place to test his conviction that his 'new
model' of television can travel successfully outside Canada.
</TEXT>
