<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Penalties on life policies may be limited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIFE assurance companies could face limits on the charges they pass on to
customers who terminate policies before maturity under measures proposed by
a consultant to Lautro, the industry's self-regulating body.
The proposals could require companies to make significant changes to the
system of paying sales agents. The current system allows commissions to be
paid 'up-front' as soon as the policy is signed.
The proposals could also address one of the most persistent consumer
complaints about the life assurance industry - the small percentage of
premiums which are refunded to those who cancel policies early.
Those who cancel within the first two years of the policy may lose up to 100
per cent of the premiums they have paid. A recent study by the Securities
and Investments Board found that between a quarter and a third of all
policies are cancelled within the first two years.
The proposals are contained in a paper written by Mr Marshall Field, a
consulting actuary for Bacon and Woodrow, who has been asked by Lautro to
review the industry's commissions structure. Lautro will decide later this
year whether new regulations on commissions are necessary.
Mr Field argues that the industry practice of charging all the sales
commission to the cancelling policyholder may be unfair and unwise.
He says companies would have more incentive to prevent the sale of policies
to those for whom they are inappropriate if they had to bear more of the
costs themselves.
The case against charging sales costs to those who end their policies early
becomes even greater in the case of those who were sold in appropriate
policies and are being charged for the mischance.
He proposes that sales costs be passed on in the product design. Thus, the
life fund might be charged with a fixed - and publicly disclosed - amount
each month to cover the sales costs for policies which last until maturity
and those which do not.
If more policyholders maintained their contracts until maturity, the life
fund would earn additional profits.
Windsor Life, the Telford-based life assurance company, said yesterday that
Lautro has lifted a 'voluntary suspension' of its sales force. The
suspension was imposed on March 19 following a revision of train-ing and
testing procedures.
The company also said that its chief executive, Mr Brian Wood, has resigned
and has been replaced by Mr William Yelverton, head of international
operations at New York Life, Windsor's parent company.
</TEXT>
