FT  01 APR 92 / Accountants protest at proposed standard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROPOSED accounting standard on the structure of financial statements is
not detailed enough, the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales warned yesterday.
The definition of 'extraordinary items' - the one-off profits or losses from
activities outside a company's normal business - should be tightened or the
concept banned, it argued in a submission to the Accounting Standards Board.
Its comments on the first financial-reporting exposure draft (FRED 1)
produced by the board also included a proposal that exceptional items should
be separately listed, not brought together under a single heading.
Standard-setters should also focus their approach more tightly and draw a
distinc-tion between listed and unlisted companies, the institute said.
Mr Paul Rutteman, chairman of the institute's financial reporting committee,
said: 'While we agree that standards should contain principles rather than
be a detailed rulebook, a standard should contain much more guidance than is
in FRED 1.'
