<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Former BNL official says US and Italy knew of loans to Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Christopher Drogoul, the man at the centre of the scandal over more than
Dollars 4bn (Pounds 2.3bn) of improper Iraqi loans extended by the Atlanta,
Georgia, branch of Italy's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL), has broken his
silence and accused the US and Italian governments of knowing about the
loans.
Mr Drogoul is the former manager of the BNL Atlanta branch and his signature
appears on more than Dollars 2bn of medium-term loans and letters of credit
extended between 1987 and 1989.
Part of the loans helped President Saddam Hussein obtain militarily useful
technology from US and European companies that went into Iraq's nuclear,
chemical and ballistic missile projects, according to documents obtained by
the Financial Times.
Mr Drogoul was indicted last year on fraud and other charges related to the
loans, which were kept on a duplicate set of 'grey book' records outside the
normal BNL loan authorisation system.
Mr Drogoul, who has not given a press interview before, visited New York
last weekend and met Il Manifesto, a small Rome-based communist newspaper.
This morning's edition of the paper quotes the former BNL man as alleging
that the National Security Agency (NSA), the secretive US electronic
surveillance agency, intercepted the thousands of telexes between Baghdad
and BNL Atlanta and thus was aware of the loans.
Mr Drogoul also claims he kept two mid-level BNL executives in Rome informed
of his Iraqi dealings and says the bank knew 'in general terms' of the Iraqi
loans. US and Italian investigators have said in the past they believe BNL
Rome had knowledge of the transactions, a charge the bank has consistently
denied.
Mr Drogoul does not offer any evidence of direct US government knowledge of
the BNL Iraqi loans, but he traces the flow of loans from Atlanta back to
1983, when an initial US government-guaranteed Dollars 30m agricultural
credit was extended by BNL Atlanta.
</TEXT>
