FT  01 APR 92 / World Trade News: Aircraft subsidies talks resume
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC and US negotiators began last-ditch talks on subsidies for civil aircraft
manufacturers yesterday, determined to resolve remaining differences.
'We really are going into this session here tonight with the purpose of
finishing this,' said a senior EC official before the meeting began. The
talks were expected to run late into the night and could continue today even
though the two sides' self-imposed deadline for a solution expired at
midnight.
This is the third time in a fortnight that Mr Hugo Paemen, EC senior trade
negotiator, and Mr Michael Moskow, US deputy trade representative, have met
for talks centred on the level of direct government subsidies for Airbus
Industrie, the EC manufacturing consortium, and indirect grants for US
manufacturers.
Both sides have commented on the positive atmosphere of last week's
Washington talks. The problem now is working out the exact levels of subsidy
each side will allow the other and concede on behalf of its own
manufacturers. Negotiators are thought to be talking about direct subsidy
levels of between 30 and 35 per cent, compared with the EC's original offer
to reduce the level to 45 per cent.
In return, the US would have to peg indirect support to perhaps as low as 5
per cent.
