<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Pensions 'too big' say unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S three largest union groups yesterday urged the government to stop
promising their members generous pensions, Reuter reports from Rome.
Paying out so much to an increasingly ageing population was like 'sitting on
a barrel of dynamite', they warned. Some 300,000 state workers are lining up
to take advantage of a law passed last year enabling them to give up their
ordinary state pensions and transfer to a lucrative system run by the
Treasury for civil servants.
The law threatens to cost the social security service more than L6,000
trillion (million million) (Pounds 2.79bn) a year. 'This is an absurd law
which needs immediate correction,' said the CGIL, the UIL and the CISL
umbrella union groups. 'It flies in the face of all attempts to reform the
pension system.' In theory, the law offers 'golden pensions' of 100 per cent
of retirement salary to all employees in the public sector.
Italian pensions, among the most generous in the world, have long been
identified as one of the causes of the massive budget deficit but
politicians have avoided cutting them for fear of losing votes.
