<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Developer Speyhawk in deal on debts after Pounds 217m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPEYHAWK, the property developer, yesterday underlined the severity of the
UK's worst commercial property decline for more than 50 years by announcing
a Pounds 216.8m annual loss and the restructuring of more than Pounds 300m
in debts.
After announcements of refinancing talks by Olympia &amp; York and Heron
International, Speyhawk's plight provides a further illustration of a slump
which has wiped more than a quarter of the value off commercial property
since the market's peak in 1989.
Speyhawk, which has debts of Pounds 303m, is technically insolvent as its
liabilities exceed its assets by some Pounds 70m. However, its 46 banks, led
by Barclays and Citibank, have agreed to restructure its debts and provide
it with working capital over four years.
Speyhawk's shares fell from 11p to 2 1/2 p, even though City analysts had
long expected very heavy losses from the company, which had been talking to
its banks since last August.
Speyhawk has been particularly severely hit by the property crash since it
does not have rental income to cushion it from its interest costs. It relies
on selling the properties it builds but has been stymied by the shortage of
demand.
It has a high exposure to the City of London, which is the worst-hit market
in the country, as a result of over-building and the recession in financial
services. More than half of the Pounds 205m provisions Speyhawk made against
its properties are due to two City buildings, Cannon Bridge and Exchequer
Court. Development sites also suffered heavy write-downs to as little as 20
per cent of former values.
The problems of companies like Speyhawk stem from the coincidence of
recession and an unprecedented amount of new building. The surge resulted
from a relaxation of planning controls, demand for technically improved
buildings and a large increase in bank lending for commercial property,
which rose to a record Pounds 40bn last year. Mr Trevor Osborne, chairman of
Speyhawk and president of the British Property Federation, said the
experience had been 'chastening'. But he thought there would be no need for
further write-downs and the company's properties would increase in value
over the next four years.
Shareholders will receive information on a planned restructuring of share
capital when a final agreement is reached with the banks. 'Shareholders
should not expect to receive dividends for some time,' Mr Osborne said. The
company said it had 'drastically' reduced its overheads, by cutting its
staff from 350 people to 47 people. Turnover fell by 71 per cent from Pounds
262.6m to Pounds 76.4m in the year to September 30 1991. The loss per share
was 829.7p, after a loss of 27.8p last year.
Lex, Page 24 Details, Page 26 London stocks, Page 44
</TEXT>
