<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / BR order may save 1,500 Brel jobs in York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday said British Rail had found the money to place a
Pounds 130m order which could save 1,500 jobs at Brel, Britain's biggest
railway carriage maker, in York, the most marginal Conservative seat.
Mr Roger Freeman, transport minister, has written to Mr Conal Gregory, the
Conservative candidate who won York in 1987 by only 147 votes, revealing
that BR planned shortly to place an order for 188 Networker coaches for
Network SouthEast.
The government had been under pressure from Mr John Prescott, Labour's
transport spokesman, who had urged Mr Malcolm Rifkind, transport secretary,
to allow BR to place an immediate order with Brel.
BR confirmed yesterday that it expected to place the order by mid-April,
although it may not necessarily go to Brel. The only other competitor is
Metro-Cammell, part of GEC Alsthom.
British Rail also announced that it and Brel had ended a long-running
dispute over the cost of modifications and repairs to the 447 Class 158
trains being built, mainly for regional services.
The settlement was announced as Asea Brown Boveri, Europe's largest
electrical engineering group, acquired Trafalgar House's 40 per cent stake
in Brel, to double its own shareholding to 80 per cent. The other 20 per
cent is owned by Brel's management and employees. British Rail sold Brel in
April 1989. Although the terms of the deal were not revealed, it is
understood that the Swedish-Swiss group, paid a nominal sum, believed to be
Pounds 1, for the stake. Trafalgar's loan stock in Brel, worth about Pounds
13m, is due to be repaid by Brel in 1994-95.
Trafalgar, the property and shipping conglomerate, recently reported a
Pounds 26.5m provision against its investment and had made no secret of its
unhappiness with its involvement in Brel.
Its investment has been written down to Pounds 1 because of Brel's mounting
losses and adverse publicity arising from defects in the Class 158 express
trains.
Brel's York works will complete its current contract for 200 Class 465
trains for Network SouthEast in a year's time and badly needs the follow on
order to remain viable.
ABB and Trafalgar House installed Mr Bo Sodersten, an experienced railway
executive, as Brel's new chief executive to replace Mr Peter Holdstock six
months ago. Since then, Brel has cut 1,000 jobs and substantially
reorganised its new construction division.
Mr Bill Beaman, secretary of the works committee at York, welcomed ABB's
purchase of Trafalgar's stake, while Mr Sodersten said the deal would
produce much greater synergies between Brel and ABB's transport division.
About 70 per cent of Brel's business is with BR and it has had very little
success at winning overseas orders in a market plagued by overcapacity.
</TEXT>
