<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Labour claims breakthrough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK last night claimed a breakthrough in the general election
campaign after three opinion polls indicated that Labour would move into the
final week with a lead of between four and seven points over the
Conservatives.
The surveys, which shocked the Conservative campaign team, are the first to
suggest that one party has taken a decisive advantage. They show a slump in
support for the Conservatives after last week's row over the health service
and criticism of Mr John Major's 'negative' campaigning.
Mr Paddy Ashdown's Liberal Democrats, whose support has risen in recent
days, are shown as the main beneficiary. Labour support remains at just over
40 per cent but the Liberal Democrats have moved up from about 16 per cent
to just below 20 per cent. But if the poll results were replicated on April
9 Mr Kinnock would move into Downing Street with an overall majority.
Senior Conservatives responded by signalling that the party would redouble
its efforts to detach 'protest' voters from the Liberal Democrats and
intensify its attacks on Mr Kinnock's leadership. Some senior ministers
suggested a radical rethink might be needed.
The boost for Labour followed another day of angry exchanges over tax and
spending. Mr Major underlined again his commitment to tax cuts and Mr
Kinnock insisted he would not increase the bills of the vast majority of
taxpayers. They dismissed suggestions in an independent report that an
impending crisis in public finances would curb greatly their respective
ambitions.
The largest Labour lead came in a Mori poll for The Times today, which gave
it 42 per cent against the Tories' 35 per cent and the Liberal Democrats' 19
per cent. A Harris survey for ITN's News At Ten put Labour on 41 per cent,
the Conservatives on 35 per cent and the Liberal Democrats on 19 per cent.
An ICM poll for The Guardian had the parties at 41, 37 and 18 respectively.
The Mori poll emphasised that Labour has retained its strong lead on the
NHS, while the Harris survey suggested that more of the skilled working
classes - the so-called C2s - have switched their allegiance to Mr Kinnock.
A series of polls in marginal constituencies - including one suggesting that
Mr Chris Patten, the party chairman, would lose Bath - reinforced the gloomy
news for the Conservatives.
Mr Major refused to comment on the poll findings but senior ministers
admitted they had been taken by surprise by the scale of the apparent swing
against the Conservatives. Some predicted another agonising inquest into
their lacklustre campaign. There were suggestions that if the results were
confirmed in polls due today, the party could be forced into a complete
shake-up of its election strategy and team.
Mr Michael Heseltine gave a flavour of the expected onslaught on Mr Kinnock
in a scathing speech yesterday questioning the Labour leader's fitness for
office. Emphasising Mr Kinnock's policy reversals, the environment secretary
said a Tory defeat would lead to government by 'a great big load of
Kinnocks'.
Mr Patten signalled that greater efforts would be made to convince potential
supporters of Mr Ashdown that a vote for the third party would help Mr
Kinnock into Downing Street.
Mr Kinnock attributed the poll findings to the contrast between his
'positive' campaign and the 'desperately negative' approach of the Tories.
He said the polls were in line with constituency and regional surveys which
had shown his party doing well in key marginals: 'We will be making large
gains and forming the majority government.'
Labour signalled its intention to move the campaign on to what it regards as
strongest ground  - the welfare state  - with the launch yesterday of its
Pounds 600m package to improve education. Today there will be a return to
the offensive on health, with Mr Kinnock renewing the charge that the NHS is
being privatised.
The Conservatives will attempt to switch the focus to Mr Kinnock's record on
defence. That will follow the election broadcast last night which portrayed
the Labour leader as a man who, after 30 years' membership of the Campaign
for Nuclear Disarmament, could not be trusted to maintain the country's
nuclear defences. Mr Patten challenged Mr Kinnock to disclose how many
Labour candidates were in CND after releasing documents indicating that all
references to the organisation had been excised from Labour's official list
of candidates.
