<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLATINUM stood out in a lack-lustre precious metals market yesterday, with
its price putting on Dollars 4.25 at Dollars 358 a troy ounce. Traders
attributed the rise to a statement by Russia's Almazyuvelirexport saying it
would retain its monopoly on exports of platinum group metals. 'The market
was just relieved that the platinum will remain in secure hands and traded
up in the absence of anything else to go on,' one dealer explained. Earlier
news that Russia was giving its foreign trade bank Vneshtorgbank a monopoly
on gold sales raised concerns that Almaz might lose control of platinum and
that supplies of the white metal might be allowed to flood on to the market.
Constructive US economic indicators helped most base metals prices to end
firm at the London Metal Exchange. The most notable rise was in the NICKEL
market, where the cash quotation closed Dollars 60 up at Dollars 7,400 a
tonne on constructive chart signals, taking it out of its recent narrow
trading range. COFFEE prices fell further in the morning but steadied in the
afternoon in what traders saw as a technical correction.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
