<HEADLINE>
FT  01 APR 92 / Lautro may limit penalties for early ending of policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIFE assurance companies could face limits on the charges they pass on to
customers who terminate policies before maturity, under measures proposed by
a consultant to Lautro, the industry's self-regulatory body.
The proposals could require companies to make significant changes to the
system of paying sales agents.
The current system allows commissions to be paid 'up-front' as soon as the
policy is signed.
It could also address one of the most persistent complaints about the life
assurance industry - the small percentage of premiums which are refunded to
those who cancel policies early.
Those who cancel within the first two years of the policy may lose up to 100
per cent of premiums paid. A recent study by the Securities and Investments
Board found that between a quarter and a third of all policies are cancelled
within the first two years.
The proposals are contained in an expository paper written by Mr Marshall
Field, a consulting actuary for Bacon and Woodrow, who has been asked by
Lautro to review the industry's commissions structure.
Lautro will decide later this year whether new regulations on commisssions
are necessary.
In the paper, Mr Field argues that the industry practice of charging all the
sales commission to the cancelling policyholder may be unfair and unwise.
Companies would have more incentive to prevent mis-selling - the sale of
policies to those for whom they are inappropriate - if they had to bear more
of the costs themselves.
The case against charging sales costs to those who end their policies early
becomes even greater in the case of those who were mis-sold policies and are
being charged for the mischance.
He proposes that sales costs be passed on in the product design. Thus, the
life fund might be charged with a fixed - and publicly disclosed - amount
each month to cover the sales costs both for policies which last until
maturity and those which do not.
Should more policyholders maintain their contracts until maturity, the life
fund would earn additional profits.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
