FT  01 APR 92 / Pledge by Gould on County Hall use
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR said yesterday it was determined to use County Hall, the former home
of the Greater London Council, as the headquarters of its proposed
replacement for the GLC.
That means a Labour government would exercise an opt-out clause in the
contract selling the complex to the Osaka-based Shirayama Corporation.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, said: 'We want to put the
whole site to proper use in the public sector.' He indicated that the party
expected to 'work closely' with the London School of Economics, which had
hoped before the Shirayama deal to move from its present cramped
accomodation to County Hall.
The party intends to use the building to house its planned 'slimline'
Greater London Authority, members of which are to be elected by proportional
representation. Labour believes, however, that enough room would be left to
put the building to additional public-sector use.
Mr Gould said yesterday that Labour would exercise the clause permitting the
Shirayama deal to be terminated up to the end of this year. He said the
party had 'yet to see the detail of the agreement'.
Shirayama, a family-owned property company, signed a contract last week to
buy the complex on the south bank of the Thames from the London Residuary
Body, the organisation responsible for winding up the affairs of the GLC.
Shirayama intends to convert part of the complex into a hotel, with the rest
being used for luxury flats and conference facilities.
Mr Gould said the cost of establishing the GLA would be 'very slight' and
might even yield a 'small saving to the taxpayer' from rationalising the
budgets of the various bodies whose activities it would take over.
